A sequence with two clauses stops working when one of the join keys is used to filter data using `startswith~()` function.

To reproduce:

```
PUT /idx
{
    "mappings": {
        "properties": {
            "@timestamp": {
                "type": "date"
            },
            "event": {
                "properties": {
                    "type": {
                        "type": "keyword",
                        "ignore_above": 1024
                    }
                }
            },
            "user": {
                "properties": {
                    "domain": {
                        "type": "keyword",
                        "ignore_above": 1024
                    },
                    "name": {
                        "type": "keyword",
                        "fields": {
                            "text": {
                                "type": "match_only_text"
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            },
            "winlog": {
                "dynamic": "true",
                "properties": {
                    "computer_name": {
                        "type": "keyword",
                        "ignore_above": 1024
                    }
                }
            },
            "source": {
                "properties": {
                    "ip": {
                        "type": "ip"
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

```
POST /idx/_doc
{
    "winlog": {
        "computer_name": "foo.bar.baz"
    },
    "@timestamp": "2025-06-18T12:21:37.018Z",
    "event": {
        "category": [
            "authentication"
        ],
        "code": "5145"
    },
    "user": {
        "domain": "bar.baz",
        "name": "something"
    },
    "source": {
        "ip": "192.168.56.200"
    }
}
```

```
POST /idx/_doc
{
    "winlog": {
        "computer_name": "foo.bar.baz"
    },
    "@timestamp": "2025-06-18T12:21:37.093Z",
    "event": {
        "category": [
            "authentication"
        ]
    },
    "user": {
        "domain": "BAR.BAZ",
        "name": "FOO$"
    },
    "source": {
        "ip": "192.168.56.200"
    }
}
```

The `SEQUENCE by source.ip` returns the expected sequence

```
POST /idx/_eql/search
{
  "query": "sequence by source.ip with maxspan=5s [any where event.code : \"5145\" and winlog.computer_name == \"foo.bar.baz\" ] [any where winlog.computer_name == \"foo.bar.baz\" and startswith~(winlog.computer_name, substring(user.name, 0, -1)) ]"
}
```

The same query with `SEQUENCE by source.ip, winlog.computer_name` returns no results

```
POST /idx/_eql/search
{
  "query": "sequence by source.ip, winlog.computer_name with maxspan=5s [any where event.code : \"5145\" and winlog.computer_name == \"foo.bar.baz\" ] [any where winlog.computer_name == \"foo.bar.baz\" and startswith~(winlog.computer_name, substring(user.name, 0, -1)) ]"
}
```

Notice that both records have the same `winlog.computer_name = "foo.bar.baz"` and that both clauses of the sequence also include a filter `winlog.computer_name == "foo.bar.baz"`.

Removing the filter `startswith~(winlog.computer_name, substring(user.name, 0, -1))` from the second clause, the query starts to work again

During the cluster upgrade process, any existing data streams from a previous cluster will receive default failure store state when deserialized. This default failure store state that is defined in the serialization code is invalid for normal failure store function in that it sets the failure store's `rollover_on_write` flag to be `false` and defaults the failure store indices list to be an empty list. The `rollover_on_write` flag is used to excuse this empty failure index list in several validation steps, and is relied upon to correctly initialize the failure store on its first use.

When deserializing a data stream that has no failure store state, a new state with no indices and `rollover_on_write` set to `true` should be created instead.

### Affected Resources
Any data stream that was created before 8.15.0 and has been carried forward via cluster upgrades to a version with failure store will not be able to ingest failures to the failure store.

### Work around
In the event that a data stream is upgraded and does not have `rollover_on_write` set to true for its empty failure store, a new failure store index must be transplanted into the affected data stream to initialize its state.

```javascript
// Create a new data stream which we will use to create a donor failure index.
PUT _index_template/donor-template
{
  "index_patterns": ["donor-datastream"],
  "data_stream": {},
  "template": {
    "data_stream_options": {
      "failure_store": {
        "enabled": true
      }
    }
  }
}
PUT _data_stream/donor-datastream

// Rollover the donor data stream twice to create a donor failure index that we will remove and a write index that will stay behind
POST donor-datastream::failures/_rollover
POST donor-datastream::failures/_rollover

// Remove the donor failure index from the first data stream, and add it to the affected data stream's failure indices.
POST _data_stream/_modify
{
  "actions": [
    {
      "remove_backing_index": {
        "index": ".fs-donor-datastream-2025.08.19-000002",
        "data_stream": "donor-datastream",
        "failure_store": true
      }
    },
    {
      "add_backing_index": {
        "index": ".fs-donor-datastream-2025.08.19-000002",
        "data_stream": "affected-data-stream",
        "failure_store": true
      }
    }
  ]
}

// Rollover the affected data stream to ensure it is correctly initialized
POST logs-okta.system-default::failures/_rollover

// Delete the donor data stream and its template to clean up
DELETE _data_stream/donor-datastream
DELETE _index_template/donor-template
```
